Rehashing in HashMap occurs when the number of entries exceeds the threshold defined by capacity × load factor. During rehashing, the internal array size is doubled and all existing entries are 
redistributed into new buckets using recomputed indices. This operation is expensive (O(n)), which is why pre-sizing and appropriate load factor tuning are important in high-performance systems.

