======= Immutable List of Objects =====
--- Which One to Use?
-- Use List.copyOf()

When:
You want true immutability
You want defensive copying
Building immutable DTO/domain objects

Best for immutable classes.

-- Use Collections.unmodifiableList()
When:
You only want read-only access
Internal list may still change

Immutable = An object whose state cannot be changed after it is created.

E.g.
Immutable class = final, does not contain setter methods, final fields
if child objects are immutable:
addresses = List.copyOf(addresses) => in constructor. It creates defensive copy automatically inside so need to create new ArrayList as down in Collections.unmodifiableList

If child objects are mutable

public Employee(String name, List<Address> addresses) {
    this.name = name;

    this.addresses = Collections.unmodifiableList( // prevents internal modification
            new ArrayList<>(addresses) // defensive copy
    );
}
-- another  way
addresses = Collectins.unmodifiableList(addresses) => in constructor
And return deep copy in getAddresses() if Address is not immutable otherwise it can be modified through setter methods by accessing through soft copy.

new ArrayList<>(addresses) is a shallow copy because it only copies the list structure but not the objects inside it. 
Both original and copied lists still reference the same objects. A deep copy requires creating new instances of each element inside the list as well.

==== Spring Circular Dependency ===
The best way to avoid circular dependency is redesigning the services to remove tight coupling. If unavoidable, Spring provides options like @Lazy, setter injection, or ObjectProvider, 
but constructor injection with proper design is preferred.

