-> Even though we only include spring-boot-starter-data-jpa, Hibernate is pulled in transitively as the default JPA provider, which is why we don’t need to explicitly add it.
 employeeRepository.save() -> SimpleJpaRepository -> EntityManager (persist/merge) -> Hibernate Session -> Persistence Context (1st level cache) -> Flush -> SQL (INSERT/UPDATE) -> JDBC -> Database Commit

-> When save() is called, Spring Data JPA delegates to SimpleJpaRepository, which uses EntityManager to either persist() or merge() the entity. Hibernate then manages the entity in the persistence context, 
generates SQL during flush, and executes it via JDBC inside a transaction.

-> Lazy loading fails without a transaction because Hibernate requires an open persistence context to fetch associated entities. When the session is closed after the repository method, accessing a lazy property 
triggers LazyInitializationException since Hibernate cannot initialize the proxy without an active session.
Lazy loading does NOT survive beyond @Transactional unless OSIV is enabled — which is why DTOs or fetch joins are preferred in real systems.

-> JPA annotations are used to map Java objects to database tables and define relationships, constraints, and lifecycle behavior. The most important ones include @Entity, @Id, @OneToMany, @ManyToOne, and
@JoinColumn, @FetchType, @Cascade

-> If a legacy system uses Hystrix, the modern approach is to migrate to Resilience4j, preferably via Spring Cloud Circuit Breaker abstraction. Migration is done gradually by wrapping service calls, replacing 
@HystrixCommand with @CircuitBreaker, and eventually removing Hystrix dependencies, ensuring zero downtime and backward compatibility.
Hystrix = heavy old framework, @CircuitBreaker = lightweight modern pattern implementation with bilkhead pattern.

